# tooling-state-skip-label-recovers-skip-capped-prs — History

## v2.0.0 (2026-06-23)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus PR #1584 "stop wrongly applying state:skip in a self-perpetuating cycle" (+ companion fixes #1572, #1575, #1589)
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Reframed the core understanding from "recover manually" to "the script was
  wrongly ADDING `state:skip` in a self-perpetuating cycle — the root cause is
  fixed; prevention shipped." This is a MAJOR bump because the recommendation
  changed: operators no longer need to babysit a cycle, the automation no
  longer creates the trap.
- Documented the three stacked defects behind the self-perpetuating cycle
  (sticky-skip non-recovery, repo-level rc mis-attribution, closed-issue
  bypass) as new Failed Attempts rows.
- Documented the FIX (state:skip is operator-only and absolute, read live;
  the script never adds it spuriously): implementer drops
  `_should_recover_stale_skip`; ci_driver gains a `pending_review` bucket;
  loop_runner gains `_filter_open_issues` + `_issue_owns_genuinely_failing_pr`;
  pr_manager gains the shared `pr_is_genuinely_stuck` classifier.
- Added a "Verified Workflow" note that the prevention fix shipped and was
  confirmed by a clean end-to-end run.
- Upgraded verification from `verified-local` to `verified-ci` (the fix merged
  and a clean run confirmed it).
- Added `history` frontmatter field referencing this file.

### Why

v1.0.0 only documented the OPERATOR RECOVERY for an already-stranded
skip-capped PR. It correctly described `state:skip` as sticky but treated the
stickiness as inherent ("a SAFETY cap, but it is STICKY"). Investigation found
the real root cause: the automation loop was itself wrongly ADDING `state:skip`
every loop in a self-perpetuating cycle on issues [1554 OPEN, 1552 CLOSED],
accomplishing nothing across all 5 loops. Three stacked defects combined into a
deadlock: the implementer refused to recover whenever an OPEN PR existed; the
repo-level drive-green rc was mis-attributed to every issue in the batch (a
green-but-unarmed-pending-review PR landed in needs_action -> rc=1 -> spurious
skip); and CLOSED issues pinned via `--issues` bypassed the open-state filter.

The fix (PR #1584) makes `state:skip` OPERATOR-ONLY and ABSOLUTE — the
automation must NEVER remove it and never auto-recover; it is read LIVE from the
GitHub issue. The fix stops the script from wrongly ADDING it. After #1584 and
companions #1572 (review-loop off-by-one), #1575 (no-commit retry), and #1589
(remaining bugs) merged, a clean run (output.log 2026-06-23 20:52, issues
1550,1548) merged PR #1590 with 0 errors, 0 skips and excluded closed #1550
from the phase loop.

The v1.0.0 operator-recovery content remains correct and is kept: removing the
label by hand (`gh issue edit <N> --remove-label state:skip`) is still the
right move for an ALREADY-stranded PR, because the script never removes it.

